 horses\nand draft pack and saddle mules, at\nSan Antonio, Texas, will be received\nhere until 12 m., central time, June 18,\n1908. Proposals for delivery at other\nprominent railroad points will also\nbe entertained. U. S. reserves right\nto reject any or all bids, or any part\nthereof. Information and blank pro\nposals furnished on application. En\nvelopes containing proposals should\nbe endorsed \"Proposals for public ani\nmals,\" and addressed to Lieut. Col.\nRobt. R Stevens, C. Q. M.\nWEDNESDAY. JUNE 17, 1908. THE SAN ANTONIO LIGHT. WEDNESDAY, JUNE 17, 1908.\nBUSINESSMEN\nPOINT TO THE\nCITES NEEDS\nLocal Captains of Trade Get\nTogether Right Royally at\nClub Meeting.\nSan Antonio got together at the\n\"get together\" mass meeting at the\nBusiness Men\u2019s club last night. There\nwire about 150 members present, rep\nresentative of the business interests\noi San Antonio, which considering\nthe tempting coolness of the oi>en air\nresorts and the numbers who seek\ncountryside roads every evening, was\na good showing.\n\"More railroads,\u201d \"more street im\nprovement,\" \"packing house.\"\u2019 These\nwere some of the keynotes of the\nspeeches made at the rally, and every\nsentiment that te|ided towards de\nvelonment of San Antonio and the\ngreat southwest evoked applause.\nJames L. Slayden used to be presi\ndent of the Business Men\u2019s club; in\nfact was the first president the club\nhad after it had succeeded the defunct\nMerchants\u2019 Exchange. According to\nC. B. Mullaly, now president. Mr.\nSlav den worked hard for the advance\nment of San Antonio, and now that\nLe is congressman from this district\nis working harder and more effective\nly filar, ever.\nMj. Slayden\u2019s address last night\nwas the feature of the meeting. It\nteemed with not only prophecies as\nto the future, but facts of the pres\nent. That San Antonio would within\na very few years have at Leon Springs\nthe largest, save one, of the military\nposts of the nation was one of the\ncongressman's prophecies, and he\nbacked it up with a statement of\nwhat congress already had done in\nthis direction. Mr. Slayden said that\nin the development of the southwest\nmore railroads were needed and he\ntraced the history of railroad building\nin Texas. He alluded to the speech\nof R. F. Yoakum delivered a couple\nof months ago at Fort Worth and en\ndorsed it in so far as declaring that\nwhile the railroads in the past had\nnot dealt any too fairly with the\npeople it must be realized that the\npeople could not deal anything but\nfairlv with the railroads which were\nthe developers of the country.\nMr. Slayden dealt also upon the ne\nccssitv of good roads, and pointed out\nthe necessity, at least, of providing\nfirst class highways throughout Bexar\ncounty. Rapid communication with\nSprings, he declared, would do\nmore for the advancement of the in\nterests of the farmers of Bexar coun\ntv than any other one project. This\nwas taken as an endrosement of the\nproposed bond issue for the building\nof better highways.\nL. J. Hart, chairman of the publici\nty committee of the realty men, told\nabout the co-operation between that\norganization and the Business Men's\nc\u2019t.j and referred to the good work\naccomplished by Secretary John B.\nCarrington. Mr. Carrington when\ncalled upon read a report of the con\ndition of the club, showing the finan\ncial condition to be excellent.\nNat M. Washer held to the five\nminute rule, but in that time put\nforth ideas worthy of notice upon tue\npart of every San Antonian. \"We\nneed a packing house; two railroads,\none to the northwest and one to the\nsouth; to educate our farmers to the\nraising of hogs, and the building of\nbetter roads,\u201d said Mr. Washer, who\nadded that so far as the packing house\nproject Is concerned he waited for\n20 years in Fort Worth to see the\nflackeries come, and would wait in\nSan Antonio.\nCol. Oscar Guessaz wanted to see\neverybody get together on the new\nhotel and T. L. Conroy spoke in be\n-1 If of the same project, asking that\nthe club at an early date take up the\nmatter of a.tdlng the promoters in\ntheir undertaking to give this city\nthe greatest hotel in the southland.\nJ. N Brown, a former president of\nthe club, told of the early day strug\ngles and latter day triumphs of the\nclub, and A. J. Bell spoke of the ever\nincreasing value of 'he country con\ntributary to San Antonio.\nC I Klnslev. from the standpoint\nof a former railroad man. spo\u00dfe of\nthe necessity of additional steeled\nhighways leading out of San Antonio\nB. L. Temple. H. L. Lathrop, V. P.\nBrown and W L. Holder all spoke\nalong the lines of improvement and\ndevelopment.\nC. B. Mullalv. president of the club\npeaidel. and refreshments were dis\nributed throughout the evening.\nBUSINESSMEN\nMAKE PROTEST i\n\nNew York, June 17. \u2014The Merchants I\nassociation of New York has an-\nnounced that it sent a telegram to\nthe chairman of the republican na\ntlonal convention protesting against\nthe insertion of any anti-injunction\nplank In the republican platform i\nCopies of the protest were sent also\nto Congressmen Parsons. Olcott and\nBennett with a request that they en- i\nleaver to obtain the united opposition\nof the New York delegation against\nany such plank.\nDangerous.\n(Yale Record.)\n\"Has he any aim in life?\u201d\n\"Well, he's always loaded.\u201d\nHandicapped.\n(Pittsburg Post.)\n\"Why can't they write an American I\ngrand opera?\"\n\"We have no peasantry to bring in\nas a chorus.\u201d\njW For the Democratic National Convention lA\n1 \u201cTHE DENVER SPECIAL\u201d\n3 (VIA FORT WORTH AND DENVER CITY RY.) S\nFt! Will afford Advantages Not Otherwise Obtainable and will be operated under conditions to meet the requirements of the most exacting! k |K\nW In addition to serving all meals enroute in elegant fully-equipped dining cars at city prices and upon the 'pay-only-for what-you-eat' plan\nW (this being a regular feature of our threugh-trains) and providing fo* 'ill comers the usual complement of other first-class \u2019equipment required M\nin modern long-distance trains: this train, in order to accommodate to heu; advantage some of the hundreds who will go and to provide a\nSS limited number of them convenient, creditable and altogether satisfactory sleeping accommodations while in Denver, at an expense running Sj\nFly SO to ,\u2018.O per cent les.; than would be possible to secure at first-class hotels after arrival In the Convention City, will also carry, extra, a number nA\nAf> of Pullman's Best Tourist Bleepers. Ma\nW Some cf those extra sleepers (of which there will be but a limited number) will be \u2018Parked' for sleeping pinposes during the Convention,\nconvenient of access and immediately adjacent Denver Union Station, \u2014from which stieet carr will be available every two minutes; this being\na feature of money saving importance, and possessing advantage of location not approachable by or via any other Texas line.\nWL As the ticket rate\u201d for this occasion will be unusually low (approximately one fare for the rotin l trip) and these special lodging accommo-\ndatlot e wi'l necessarily be limited in number, prompt applications for snnie will be necessary in order to secure choice assignments; the ex- <A\nhU pense of which will be but $l2 50 per double-berth for the most favorabli and $lO.lO per berth for the balance, for the entire round trip of e.ight CM\nSr daye; each berth oeing large enough for two persons. For one-way Sleeper acccmnndatlomi, rate of 82.50 per berth will apply.\n\u25bc1 This train will leave Fort Worth via \u201cTHE DENVER ROAD\u201d at 9;30 a. m. Sunday, July sth, will arrlv* Denver during the early afternoon IV\naJ of the tallowing day and will leave Denver, returning, at 10:00 p. m. July 11th. Spe -ial representatives will accompany this train and be in\nCa charge of all special arrangements. Applications for reservations, and remittances to cover, rliould be promptly made to S 3\nxu A. A. GLISSON. Gvn'l. Pass. Agt.. Fort Worth. Texass am\nM SPECIAL NOTE:\u2014For both going and return trip we offer Double Daily Solid Through-Train Service; thus avoiding changes of cars of any wj\nclass and the possibility of broken connections at junctions, enroute. No other Texas Line does. Kf\nMEDALS FOR PUPILS OF\nST. MICHAEL\u2019S SCHOOL\nThe annual commencement exer\ncises of St. Michael\u2019s school, which\nwere held in St. Albert\u2019s hall in Cen\nter street yesterday afternoon, were\nlargely attended. St. Michael\u2019s school\nis a Polish Catholic institution with.\nSister Mary Stanislaus as mother su-\u2018!\nperl or. The enrollment for the term\njust closed was 106.\nAn excellent program was carried\nout. It opened with piano selection\u2019\nby Miss Elsie Schott. Miss Thekla\nklabunde. Miss Theresa Obets, Mis\u2019\nEva Maffi, Miss Emilie W;tte and\nMaster Nicky Maffi. The address of\nwelcome was delivered by Miss Es\ntelle Braemen in a clever manner.\nMiss Gussie Zimmerman and class\nentertained the audience with a skit\nentitled \"The Bogus School Inspec\ntor,\" and Miss Valeria Sobieski gave\na Polish recitation, which was mucn\nenjoyed. Joseph Sobieski gave a reci.\ntation. Miss Estelle Braemen sang a\nsong and the junior boys\u2019 class and\nthe senior girls' class executed a very\npretty march and drill.\nThe Misses Mary Dausin. Celia\nDanysch and Dora Danyseh rendered\na Polish dialogue and the boys and\ngirls of the junior class sang a Polish\nsong. Misses Viola Laue. Margaret\nObets, Florence Granger, Helen Head\nNona Thompson and Hilda Jaeckle\nperformed on the piano.\nFather Dabrowski, pastor of St\nMichael's church, delivered an ad\ndress and awarded medals to the fol\nlowing pupils:\nMiss Anna Pollock. Miss Viola\nSobieski. Miss Tbekla Klabunde, Miss\nMary Dausin. Miss Celia Danysch,\nMiss Helen Head, Miss Julia Icke,\nMiss Theresa Obets. Miss Eva Maffi,\nMiss Margaret Obets and Joseph\nLudwig. Anton Ceerszenski, Joseph\nSobieski and Stanley Gorrel.\nAr-aw-\nPROOF OF WEALTH\nSire\u2014Are you capable of supporting\nmy daughter In good atyle? Are you\u2014-\nSultor-Rlcn ,1? Why. I have been\nable to suppiy her with bon-bone and\ntheatre tlckeie far the laet ela months:\nHelp for a\nWeak Stomach\nIt is so common nowadays to find a\nperson with a weak stomach. They\ncan\u2019t eat this and that and confine them*\nselves to a diet that would scarcely keep\nan infant alive.\nHowever, that won\u2019t cure the trouble.\nIf you can\u2019t eat ordinary healthful food\nwithout suffering then there is something\ntne matter with your stomach, and you\nought to get it attended to. Don\u2019t deny\nyourself the pleasures of life, but get\nDr. Caldwell\u2019s Syrup Pepsin and let it\nstrengthen your stomach muscles and\ntone up your whole digestive system.\nThen you will be well.\nMra. Walker Janea. of Bucyrna. O had a\nweak stomach for a long time, until one day she\nhappened to be in Birk Broe. drug store and in\nquired about It and they recommended Dr.\nCaldwell's Syrup Pepsin. She took it and in\nnow perfectly healthy and well. Much the same\ncan be said of Mr. Collins, of Pembroke, Va.\nwho suffered a stroke of paralysis which left\nhim with a weak stomach. He tried various\nkinds of medical treatment and medicines with\nout success, then took Dr. Caldwell's Syrup\nPepsin and was cured. Thousands of others\ncan tell stories of weak stomachs wonderfully\nstrengthened by the use of this groat remedy.\nIt cannot be too highly recotntneuded In all\nstomach, liver and bowel complaints In old and\nyoung. Its gentle action and pleasant taste\nrecommend It eepecially to women and chil\ndren. and to all. In fact, who believe that a laxa\ntive can be effective even It It does not taste bad.\nWe cannot urge you too strongly to take this\ngrand remedy in constipation, dyspepsia, weak\nstomach, liver trouble, biliousness, etc. You\ncan buy a W cent or $1 bottle of your druggist\nand he will guarantee it to do